          "body": "Three months after the prose call, Zechariah receives the first of eight night visions. He sees a man on a red horse standing among myrtle trees in a ravine, with a company of red, sorrel, and white horses behind him. The myrtle is significant: in Isaiah 41:19 and 55:13 the myrtle replaces the thorn as a sign of Zion's restoration. The ravine — a place of lowliness and obscurity — mirrors the current condition of the returned community. The horsemen are divine reconnaissance agents sent to 'patrol the earth' (1:10), and their report is theologically disturbing: 'all the earth is peaceful and quiet' (1:11). This is not good news. Pax Persica — the enforced calm of Darius's empire — meant that the nations that had devastated Judah were prospering while Jerusalem lay in ruins. The world's ease was not God's blessing; it was the backdrop against which Zion's desolation was most visible. The vision forces the community to see what they already knew: the nations were comfortable, and God had not yet acted on the covenant promises."
