        "title": "The man among the myrtles — divine surveillance and the problem of Pax Persica",
        "range": "1:7-11",
        "excerpt": "We have patrolled the earth, and behold, all the earth is peaceful and quiet.",
        "body": "The transition to the night visions in verse 7 is abrupt and total. Zechariah moves from prose proclamation to visionary experience — a shift in register that marks a shift in the nature of revelation. The interpreting angel, the divine horsemen, and the 'man standing among the myrtle trees' constitute a divine council scene, a genre well-attested in the Old Testament (1 Kings 22:19-22; Isaiah 6; Job 1-2) in which the prophet is granted access to heavenly deliberation.\n\nThe identification of 'the man on the red horse' who stands among the myrtles (1:8) and is called 'the angel of the LORD' (1:11-12) has generated sustained scholarly discussion. The convergence of the 'man' who directs the patrol (1:10), the 'angel of the LORD' who intercedes (1:12), and the divine response in 1:13 suggests this is a theophanic figure — a pre-incarnate appearance of the second person of the Trinity, a reading held by Calvin, Keil and Delitzsch, and many Reformed commentators. The figure both commands the divine agents and intercedes before the Father, a mediatorial role consistent with the Angel of the LORD in Genesis 18, Exodus 3, and Joshua 5:13-15.\n\nThe myrtle trees in a ravine are a deliberate symbolic setting. The myrtle was associated with covenantal blessing and the restoration of Zion (Isaiah 41:19; 55:13 — where myrtle replaces the thorn as a sign of the new creation). The ravine (Hebrew *metsullah*, the deep place or hollow) locates the divine representative at the lowest point of the landscape — a visual emblem of Israel's current position: low, obscured, not yet exalted. God's presence is not absent from the depth; He stands there.\n\nThe horsemen's reconnaissance report — 'all the earth is peaceful and quiet' (1:11) — is the vision's theological crisis. Pax Persica was real. Darius I had consolidated the empire by 519 BC; the Mediterranean world was stable and the nations were at ease. But Jerusalem still lay in rubble and the temple still stood unbuilt. The world's calm was not Israel's peace. The angel of the LORD's intercession in verse 12 — 'how long will You have no compassion for Jerusalem?' — is the correct theological response to the reconnaissance report: the world's prosperity does not justify Zion's continued desolation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Hadas* (myrtle) appears in Isaiah 41:19 and 55:13 as a symbol of messianic restoration — the choice of this tree as the setting of the vision is not incidental. *Metsullah* (ravine/hollow) is used of the depths of the sea in Exodus 15:5 and Psalm 107:24 — here it evokes profound lowliness. *Shaqat* (quiet/at rest, v. 11) is the same word used of the land resting in Judges 3:11, 30 — but here it describes the nations' unchallenged ease, not covenant peace."
